element.name: Epidemiologist-Developer
element.documentation: Someone with both epidemiological and software development experience who is developing and evaluating scientific models to try and measure risk, exposure, and control effects for a DCT app or DCTS.

element.name: DCT App User
element.documentation: An end user of a DCT app. Typically a resident of a country or state with a public health authority. Normally PHAs provide a DCT app, but it may also be a private company for its own staff.

element.name: Epidemiologist
element.documentation: An Epidemiologist without computer science knowledge or skills. They are trying to stop the spread of a disease.

element.name: Public Health Authority (PHA)
element.documentation: A Public Health Authority who have staff with a range of skills but who are trying to protect a population from the spread of a disease by providing advice and systems to control the spread.

element.name: Contact Tracer
element.documentation: Somebody working for a PHA that is trying to trace and contact those who have been at risk of disease exposure. May not be a trained epidemiologist.

element.name: Vulnerable Community
element.documentation: A group of DCT app users whose geographic remoteness or social standing (E.g. lack of wealth) may mean that some technology approaches available to richer members of a country or state are not open to them. This is a KEY GROUP within Herald's design goals. It includes, but is not limited to, those who are elderly, or very young, or homeless, in traditional communities, are poor, do not have access to ICT, do not have regular Internet/Data connectivity for devices, or are disabled and find using technology difficult.

element.name: Hostile State Actor
element.documentation: A nation state who is trying to compromise a DCTS system for economic, military, political, or society disruption / propaganda reasons. They may want to access DCTS data of another nation to track people or force people in to a location at a time of their choosing. (aka 'the Westminster attack')

element.name: Domestic Abuser
element.documentation: Someone who seeks to control and monitor an individual through technical and emotional abuse/coercion means. They may misuse data in a DCT app to see that a person is mixing with others or travelling out of area.

element.name: Organised Crime
element.documentation: Well funded and organised groups that would seek to exploit a DCTS for economic gain or individual coersion

element.name: Herald for C++
element.documentation: Main reference implementation since v1.3. All new features are defined and tested here first. Swift and iOS Herald libraries are really specialisations of the C++ project's components.

element.name: Herald Hardware
element.documentation: Opensource hardware designs. May also include specialist hardware driver code for devices not supported by Zephyr natively.

element.documentation: From GovTech in Singapore

element.name: Herald for Node.js
element.documentation: Adapter library - exposes the Herald C++ API into Node.js exports. Thin adapter layer.

element.name: Exposure Instance ID
element.documentation: For a human, the DCT hash ID. For other sources, their IDs. E.g. radiation whether a local dosemeter or one from a building's beacon.

element.name: Exposure Period
element.documentation: Start and End date times. For 'live raw exposures', the last time for which a reading was given in the period.

element.name: Exposure Amount
element.documentation: Double for now. Perhaps a more complex value in future.

element.name: Agent
element.documentation: E.g. HumanProximity, UVRadiation, OutdoorLight, IndoorLight, AudioLoudness

element.name: Exposure Class ID
element.documentation: E.g. BluetoothRSSIMinutes, AudioDistanceEstimateSeconds, LumensMinutes, RadMinutes, etc.

element.name: Risk State
element.documentation: E.g. Potential Risk (non confirmed cases), presumptive risk, confirmed risk (E.g. from exposure notification confirmation after PCR testing)

element.name: Exposure Change Delegate
element.documentation: E.g. Exposure Confidence Updated (wasConfidence, nowExposure), Live Exposure Changed (was, now)

element.name: Risk Score Algorithm
element.documentation: Calculate Risk Score (Exposure Manager, Configuration, Metadata) -> Risk Score, Update Risk Score (WasScores (Periods may overlap), Exposure Change Details) -> Risk Score

relationship.name: Update measure confidence
relationship.documentation: For human proximity, the status of the individual you are proximate to (presumed healthy, symptomatic-untested, tested-positive, tested-negative) would affect the confidence score, which in turn would trigger the exposure manager to update the risk score.

node.label: Lowercase components are packages/namespaces, uppercase are classes/structs.
Exposures are things that can be directly measured to some degree of accuracy. E.g. Proximity to a person, temperature, UV, radiation.
Risks are things that can be estimated from information about the person at risk, and the risk environment (such as exposures). E.g. Risk of having contracted COVID-19.
All projects have Herald for C++ as an upstream dependency. It will therefore be necessary to tightly test and control C++ API releases.
